Mercury(II) perchlorate, with a chemical formula of Hg(ClO4)2·nH2O, is an inorganic compound where n can range between zero and six. The anhydrous form and its various hydrates are toxic, water-soluble and display hygroscopic properties as white solids. The preparation of mercury(II) perchlorate hydrates commonly involves reacting mercury(II) oxide with concentrated perchloric acid: HgO +2 HClO4 →Hg(ClO4)2 + H2O; evaporation of this solution results in the formation of hexahydrate (Hg(ClO4)2·6H2O), which can be converted to lower hydrates like dihydrate by heating to 30 °C in a vacuum. Further heating doesn't produce the anhydrous form but instead forms a basic mercury perchlorate. The anhydrous form is produced by dehydrating the dihydrate using anhydrous perchloric acid or dichlorine hexoxide. In aqueous solutions, mercury(II) perchlorate reacts strongly with aqueous ammonia to produce [Hg(NH3)4](ClO4)2. It also reacts with elemental mercury to form mercury(I) perchlorate (Hg(ClO4)2 + Hg → Hg2(ClO4)2). The hexahydrate (Hg(ClO4)2·6H2O) has a trigonal crystal structure, consisting primarily of [Hg(H2O)6]2+ centers and ClO4– ions. The anhydrous form consists of monodendate perchlorate ions, as determined by IR spectroscopy analysis. Mercury(II) perchlorate has limited applications in organic synthesis, such as in the hydrolysis of vinyl halides and the allylation of isatins and isatin ketoimines.

Camptoceras terebra is a species of small freshwater snail, an aquatic gastropod mollusc in the family Planorbidae, commonly known as the ram’s horn snails, characterized by coiled, sinistral (left-handed) shells and association with slow-moving or stagnant freshwater habitats. == Taxonomy == Camptoceras terebra was described by William Henry Benson in 1843 and is the type species for its genus. One source classifies Camptoceras hirasei as a subspecies (Camptoceras terebra hirasei). One syntype is in London's Natural History Museum collections. == Description == The long, skinny shell has a height of 6 to 7 mm and a diameter of 3 mm, with a maximum height of about 9 mm and an aperture size of about 4 mm in the largest dimension. The shell's whorls curve left and are not fused; varices (projections) may serve as sculpture on its surface resembling Epitonium's varices but without spiral striae present. This species has proportionally large eyes.
